column168: RESPONDER CALLED TO LEAKING PACKAGE.  DONNED FULL PPE, SECURED AREA, APPLIED DECISION TREE, IDENTIFIED CONTENTS AND MOVED TO A MORE SECURE AREA. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND HARMFUL STOW AWAY FROM FOODSTUFFS RESPONSE SHEET.  SOLIDIFIED WITH CLAY BASED ABSORBENT.  DAMAGED MATERIALS WERE PROCESSED THROUGH UPS DMP.  DESIGNATED RESPONDER:  JOE WEBBER

PACKAGE WAS LOADED INTO PKG CAR PER NORMAL HAZARDOUS LOADING PROCEDURES. THE LOADER NOTICED A ODOR AND NOTIFIED THE PRELOAD SUPERVISOR.  THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE RESPONDER, WHO BY WEARING APPROPRIATE PPE TOOK THE PACKAGE OUT  OF THE CAR TO THE PROCESSING AREA WHERE IT WAS FOUND TO BE A LOOSE CAP ON THE INNER CONTAINER.  THE INNER CONTAINER CONTAINED 18.93 L OF BUTYRIC ACID WHICH USED A CAP FOR CLOSURE WITH NO INNER SEAL.  A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LEAKED OUT, LEAVING WET SPOTS ON THE INNER LINER.  THE PRODUCT WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING DMP PROCEDURES.  ALTHOUGH THE CAP HAD A PLASTIC SEAL AROUND THE OUTSIDE OF IT, THE COMBINATION OF NO INNER SEAL AND THE LEVEL TO WHICH THE CONTAINER WAS FILLED LEAD TO THE FAILURE OF THE CLOSURE.

PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY PACKED, MARKED, AND LABELED.  FEDEX PERSONNEL ACCIDENTLY DROPPED THE PACKAGE AND CAUSED THE LEAK.  PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A STEEL DRUM AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.  NO CLEAN UP WAS REQUIRED, SPILL CONTAINED WITHIN THE PACKAGE.

PACKAGE WAS REPORTED AS BEING CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT WHEN COURIER WAS MAKING DELIVERY TO CUSTOMER.  THE PACKAGE WAS BAGGED AND THE RECIPIENT TOOK RECEIPT OF THE PACKAGE.  SPILLAGE WAS LIMITED TO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND A SMALL PORTION OF THE CONCRETE AT THE CUSTOMERS SITE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH NO SPILLAGE GETTING INTO ANY SOIL OR WATERWAY.

column168: WHILE TRAVELING WEST ON I-66 IN VIRGINIA DRIVER NOTICED CLEAR LIQUID SEEPING OUT FROM UNDER DOORS OF VAN.  DIRVER PULLED OVER TO CHECK AND REALIZED HE WAS LOSING MATERIAL.  HE CALLED ME & I IN TURN CALLED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PEOPLE.  ECS ON CALL.  THEY DISPATCHED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  AFTER IT WAS DETERMINED WHERE THE LEAK WAS THE DECISION WAS MADE TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING MATERIAL FROM THE LEAKING COMPARTMENT TO THE TWO INTACT COMPARTMENTS.  THEN THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS TRANSFERED TO A LINED TANKER TO CONTINUE ON TO CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION.  THE VAN WHICH WAS USED WAS TAKEN TO OUR LOCATION IN WHARTON NJ, TO DETERMINE WHAT THE ROOT CAUSE WAS FOR THE COMPARTMENT FAILURE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT CAUSE OF LEAK CAME FROM A FAULTY REPAIR MADE BY THE VESSEL MANUFACTURER IN BUFFALO NY.  OUR REMAINING TANK VAN VESSELS WERE REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND A COMPLETE INSPECTION WAS MADE PAYING PARTICULAR ATTENTION TO AREA WHERE THE 1ST VAN FAILED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT BOTH REMAINING VANS WERE SOUND & RETURNED TO ACTIVE SERVICE.  WE ARE IN COMMUNICATION WITH THE MANUFACTURER TO MAKE REPAIRS.  ON 1ST TANK VAN & TO HAVE THEM MAKE A REPORT AS HOW THE REPAIR WAS DONE & WHY IT FAILED & WHAT CORRECTIVE ACTION IS BEING TAKEN TO ENSURE NO FUTURE FAILURES.

column168: IN RAIL YARD, BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED FRESH PRODUCT ATOP PGTX 400289 TANK SHELL.  BNSF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER/MECHANICAL FOREMAN DISCOVERED ALL SIX MANWAY COVER BOLTS LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT & THESE WERE TOOL TIGHTENED IN REQUIRED PATTERN.  NON-EVAPORATING SPILLAGE NEAR MANWAY COVER WITH SOME SIDE SHELL DRIPPAGE WAS WIPED.  TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION AFTER SECUREMENT COMPLETED BY 1130 HRS.  CDT, 5/02/03 & NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE EVIDENT.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED,  THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE TRIPLE CROWN SERVICES FACILITY AT 7150 GRAYSON ROAD IN HARRISBURG, PENNSYLVANIA, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED A POWDER RELEASING FROM TRAILER 462324.  TRIPLE CROWN SERVICES CONTACTED H.M.H.T.T.C., INC OF CARLISLE, PENNSYLVANIA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  UPON INVESTIGATION, H.M.H.T.T.C., INC DETERMINED THE POWDER RELEASED FROM A 4000 POUND SUPER SACK INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE HUNDRED POUNDS OF POWDER WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE BAG BEING TORN BY SOME RIVETS ON THE TRAILER WALL. H.M.H.T.T.C., INC.  SCRAPED THE FREE PRODUCT OFF THE AFFECTED ASPHALT SURFACE.  THE PRODUCT WAS THEN PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  THE CLEANUP SUITS AND POLY MATERIAL FROM THE CLEANUP WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  THE ORIGINAL SACK THE PRODUCT WAS IN WAS PLACED INTO A SEPARATE FIFTY FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  TRIPLE CROWN SERVICES WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL WITH THE SHIPPER, PQ CORPORATION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: CN/IC CAR MAN NOTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA TO TANK CAR NATX 37711 (L/ETHYL ALCOHOL) DURING A MECHANICAL INSPECTION IN THE CHAMPAIGN YARD, URBANA, IL.  ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER AND CN/IC HAZMAT TEAMS RESPONDED FINDING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT COMING FROM BETWEEN THE FLANGE OF THE OUTLET NOZZLE EXTENSION AND THE BALL VALVE. INCIDENT SEVERITY INDEX 5(5+3+0)(2+0) = 80 CAUSE CODE = 563.

CWX DSR FRED LACK WAS LOADING A PALLET CONTAINING 40 BAGS OF 9, UN 3077, PGIII UNDER A LOAD RACK.  HE FAILED TO PROTECT THE SIDE OF THE BAGS WITH CARDBOARD DUNNAGE.  ONE ROW OF THE PLASTIC BAGS SNAGGED ON ONE OF THE LOAD RACKS LEGS AND TORE OPEN TWO BAGS.  ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF APPROX. 2 CUPS OR 16 OUNCES OF PRODUCT.  JAMES RILEY, THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY MADE CONTACT WITH KIM MARVIN, THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR  FOR THE N CENTRAL REGION AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO GO AHEAD AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  IT WAS NOT NECESSARY TO CALL THE SHIPPER PROVIDED EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER.  THE LOST PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AND PLACED IN A 5 GAL PAIL.  THE TWO PLASTIC BAGS WERE TAPED SHUT AND LATER PLACED IN A 20 GAL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE EVENT WAS RECORDED IN THE SOS SYSTEM AS A FORKLIFT INCIDENT AND FRED LACK WAS RETRAINED ON THE FORKLIFT BY SERVICE CENTER MANAGER STEVE HELTON ON TUESDAY 05/06/03.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY FIVE GALLON FIBER DRUM WAS DISCOVERED NEAR THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, THREE TABLESPOONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY AN UNKNOWN OBJECT AT ANOTHER TERMINAL.  APPARENTLY, THE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AT ANOTHER ROADWAY TERMINAL AND TAPED TO SECURE THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE TAPE DID NOT HOLD, CAUSING THE FREE PRODUCT TO RELEASE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENTS, A BROOM AND SHOVEL. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A ONE HUNDRED AND TEN GALLON POLY OVER PACK DRUM WHICH WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS WIPED OFF AND PLACED INTO ONE, EIGHTY FIVE GALLON STEEL  OVER PACK WHICH WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THERE WAS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  TWO ROADWAY EMPLOYEES, MARY MOORE AND FRANKIE BEECH COMPLAINED OF HEADACHE AND WERE BROUGHT TO A NEARBY MEDICAL FACILITY WHERE THEY WERE SEEN AND RELEASED BACK TO WORK.  THE DSM, DAID THOMPSON WAS CONTACTED BY SPILL CENTER, INC. TO DISCUSS REPORTING.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DURING UNLOADING ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. THE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A FAULTY SEAM. THIRTY GALLONS OF INK HAD LEAKED SO AN OUTSIDE VENDOR WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVER PACKED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING A CLAY ABSORBENT.  THE SPILL MATERIAL WAS PACKAGED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS AND TRANSPORTED TO THE CONLEY, GA FACILITY.  THE SPILL MATERIAL WILL BE SENT TO THE HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE AREA AND DISPOSED OF BY AN OUTSIDE VENDOR.

WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, THE IBC WAS FOUND LEAKING.  THE IBC WAS LEAKING FROM A CRACK ON THE TOP.  THERE WERE NO PHYSICAL SIGNS OF DAMAGED TO THE IBC.  UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT, THE IBC WAS SECURED FOR SHIPMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRY AND HELD IN OVER PACKS FOR DISPOSAL.

CARRIER'S HAZMAT RECEIVED A CALL FROM A DOCK SUPERVISOR STATING THAT THERE IS A DRUM OF HAZMAT ON THE DOCK THAT APPEARS TO BE SMOKING.  THE DRUM IS ON A PALLET OF FOUR.  NONE OF THE OTHERS APPEAR TO BE AFFECTED.  HAZMAT SENT ONE SPECIALIST TO SURVEY THE SITUATION.  ONE DRUM APPEARED TO BE UNDER PRESSURE AS ITS REMOVABLE HEAD WAS DISTENDED AND THERE WAS VENTING OF DUST TAKING PLACE THROUGH THE GASKET.  THERE WAS NO HEAT ASSOCIATED WITH THE VENTING. THE DOCK WORKER WHO WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER COMPLAINED OF A BURNING SENSATION OF HIS EYES.  HAZMAT GAVE INSTRUCTIONS TO THE DOCK SUPERVISOR THAT THE WORKER SHOULD BE SEEN BY A MEDICAL PROFESSIONAL WITHOUT DELAY.  HE WAS IMMEDIATELY TRANSPORTED TO AN APPROPRIATE FACILITY.  THE DOCK SUPERVISOR SECURED THE AREA AROUND THE INCIDENT. A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER WAS REACHED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE GAVE ADVICE ON THE HAZARDS OF THE PRODUCT AND ON HOW THEY HANDLE IN PLANT INCIDENTS.  PERSONNEL IN APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT SHOULD OVER PACK THE DRUM.  THE SPECIALIST RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR TO DO SO. THE TRAILER THAT HAD CONTAINED THE SHIPMENT STILL HAD AIRBORNE PARTICLES OF THE MATERIAL.  IT WAS MOVED AWAY FROM THE DOCK.  ON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR'S PERSONNEL SET UP A NEGATIVE PRESSURE FAN IN ORDER TO REMOVE THE DUST.  THE CARRIER PROVIDED THE CONTRACTOR WITH A SUITABLE RECOVERY DRUM.  THE PRESSURIZED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO IT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE OTHER DRUMS IN THE SHIPMENT DISCLOSED THE POSSIBILITY OF FAILURE OF SEVEN OTHER DRUMS. THOSE DRUMS WERE ALSO OVER PACKED.  ON INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER, THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS PUT OUT FOR DELIVERY.  THE SICKENED EMPLOYEE REMAINED OFF DUTY FOR THE BALANCE OF HIS SHIFT BUT RETURNED WITH NO RESTRICTIONS OR COMPLAINTS FOR HIS NEXT SCHEDULED SHIFT.

WHILE AT A REST STOP ON I-95 SOUTH, MM 154 DRIVER CHECKED WAD & DISCOVERED THE LEAK.  HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED US & TOLD US WHAT WAS GOING ON.  I INFORMED DRIVER TO FIND REST AREA EMPLOYEE TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE LEAK. I THEN CONTACTED OUR INSURANCE CO & OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PEOPLE.  A&A ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ON SCENE IN LESS THAN ONE HOUR.  LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED FROM LEAKING VESSEL TO LINED TANKER.  THE MATERIAL WHICH SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED AND OUR DRIVER LEFT THE SCENE WITH THE EMPTY VESSEL. ALL OF OUR TANK VANS HAVE BEEN PLACED OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL A THOROUGH EXAMINATION IS PERFORMED TO OUR SATISFACTION THAT THEY ARE ROAD WORTHY. THE MANUFACTURER IS COMING TO OUR LOCATION WITH A TEAM TO INVESTIGATE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, A HISSING NOISE WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE CARTON CONTAINING, ONE TEN POUND STEEL CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF-WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, FIVE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE VALVE. TERMINAL PERSONNEL OPENED THE CARTON AND TIGHTENED THE LOOSE VALVE.  NO CLEANUP WAS NECESSARY.  THE CYLINDER WAS REPACKAGED IN THE ORIGINAL CARTON AND IT WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER PROCEEDING NORTHBOUND ON STATE ROUTE 507 WHEN HE MADE A SUDDEN STOP AT A TRAFFIC STOP LIGHT.  SURGE OF LIQUID IN CARGO TANK FORCED THE MATERIAL OUT DOME BETWEEN GASKET AND ITS SEALING SURFACE.  MATERIAL RAN DOWN EXTERIOR OF CARGO TANK ONTO ROADWAY.   UPON DISCOVERY, DRIVER PULLED OVER TO SHOULDER OF ROADWAY AND CALLED POLICE.  WASHINGTON STATE HIGHWAY PATROL WAS FIRST ON-SCENE AND SECURED PERIMETER.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (DOT) CALLED TO SCENE.  STATE DOT ASSUMED COMMAND AND REPORTED INCIDENT TO THE WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY (DOE).  DUE TO A LESSER AMOUNT OF MATERIAL THAT SPILLED ONTO ROADWAY AND HEAVY RAIN WAS IMMINENT AT THIS TIME, NO ACTION WAS TAKEN TO CLEANUP ROADWAY.  A GREATER AMOUNT OF MATERIAL REMAINED ON CARGO TANK, WHICH WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH VINEGAR.  DRIVER SECURED DOME AND PROCEEDED TO CONSIGNEE. DOME WAS SECURED, BUT WAS NOT TIGHT ENOUGH TO PREVENT THE LEAKS WHEN THE LIQUID MATERIAL SURGED AGAINST IT.  THE CAUSE WAS THE DRIVER'S FAILURE TO PROPERLY THE DOME COVER ON THE CARGO TANK AFTER LOADING THE MATERIAL. CARGO TANK WAS RETURNED TO OUR TERMINAL AFTER UNLOADING AND INSPECTED BY A QUALIFIED MECHANIC, HIS CONCLUSION IS THE CARGO TANK IS IN PROPER WORKING ORDER AND NO REPAIRS WHERE REQUIRED.  (SEE ATTACHED STATEMENT.) WE ARE CURRENTLY AUDITING OUR LOADING AND SECUREMENT PRACTICES TO DETERMINE IF A GAP EXISTS WITH OUR WRITTEN PROCEDURES.  WE ARE ALSO REVIEWING OUR TRAINING PROGRAM TO SEE IF OPPORTUNITIES EXIST FOR IMPROVEMENT.  PHOTOS OF THE INCIDENT ARE ATTACHED.

THE DG AGENT WAS GETTING READY TO INSPECT IT AND HAD NOTICED MANY DISCREPANCIES AND WAS PREPARING TO REFUSE THE PACKAGE WHEN HE SMELLED THE FUMES.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED UNTIL A CLEAN UP SPECIALIST COULD PROPERLY CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THE PACKAGE WAS A GLASS BOTTLE INSIDE A ZIPLOCK BAG WITH NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE BOTTLE WAS IN A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH SHREDDED NEWSPAPER ARE CUSHIONING.  THIS WAS SENT AS A LIMITED QUANTITY PACKAGE HOWEVER THE SHIPPER DECLARATION FORM NOR THE BOX CONTAINED THE MARKINGS FOR LIMITED QUANTITY.  THIS BOX COULD NOT HAVE POSSIBLY WITHSTOOD THE 1.2 METER DROP TEST OR STACKING TEST.  WHEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER FELT HIS ONLY FAULT WAS TO NOT MARKED THE BOX OR DEC WITH LTD QTY.  THE PACKAGE WAS RELEASED TO THE SHIPPER.  I CONTACTED CRAIG NUTT AT THE DETROIT FAA OFFICE AND ASKED THAT HE CHECK OUT THIS COMPANY FOR TRAINING REQUIREMENTS AND OTHER COMPLIANCE.  PHOTOS OF THE PACKAGE ARE ATTACHED.

MALFUNCTIONING VENT ON VST SPILL CONTAINED TO ASPHALT PARKING LOT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING RED-DYED DIESEL FOR OFF-ROAD USE IN HEAVY EQUIPMENT AT LA FARGE CONSTRUCTION PIT.  WHEN DRIVER CHANGED COMPARTMENTS WITH SUCTION SIDE OF HOSE WIRE THE DRIVER USED TO SECURE HOSE CONNECTION AT PUMP CAME LOOSE.  UPON OPENING VALVE TO UNLOAD NEXT COMPARTMENT, HOSE SURGED WHEN PRODUCT REACHED THE PUMP CAUSING VIBRATION.  HOSE CAMS CAME LOOSE AND HOSE CAME OFF PUMP.  ABOUT 45-50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED PRIOR TO STOPPING THE SOURCE.  DRIVER CONTAINED SPILL AT SITE CALLED TERMINAL FOR ASSISTANCE.  CSC MGR. RONNIE MCCLESKEY RESPONDED WITH ERTS FOR CLEANUP OF SITE.  HEAVY EQUIPMENT AT SITE USED TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  LIQUID RESIDUAL MATERIALS TAKEN TO UPT YARD FOR RECYCLE/TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. APPROXIMATELY 35 YARDS OF SOIL CONTAMINATED WITH RED DYED DIESEL REMAINED ON SITE AND WENT INTO THEIR RECYCLE STOCKPILE FOR GROUND BUILDING MATERIALS.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT A REST AREA ON INTERSTATE 81, NORTHBOUND, MILE MARKER 262, IN NEW MARKET, VIRGINIA, THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. DRIVER NOTICED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PAVEMENT.THE ROCKINGHAM COUNTY SHERIFF AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE REST AREA WAS CLOSED AND EVACUATED IN ORDER TO PROTECT THE PUBLIC.  HAZMAT RESPONSE OF OLATHE, KANSAS WAS CALLED BY THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. HARRISBURG, PENNSYLVANIA TERMINAL TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP.  HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTACTED HAZMAT 2000 OF HARRISONBURG, VIRGINIA TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT SCENE.  UPON INVESTIGATION, FIVE DAMAGED CARDBOARD CARTONS AND THREE UNAFFECTED CARDBOARD CARTONS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT EACH CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINED FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS.  EIGHTEEN LEAKING PLASTIC JUGS AND FOURTEEN UNAFFECTED PLASTIC JUGS WERE DISCOVERED.  APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE CARTONS BEING CRUSHED BY HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  THE TRAILER CONTENTS WERE OFF LOADED ONTO TWO OTHER ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TRAILERS AND THE THREE TRAILERS RETURNED TO THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC HARRISBURG, PA TERMINAL FOR CLEANUP.  LEVEL C PROTECTION, NEUTRALIZER, AND ABSORBENTS WERE USED IN THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED CARDBOARD CARTONS, AND EIGHTEEN LEAKING PLASTIC JUGS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY FIVE GALLON PLASTIC OVER PACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  FEDERAL AND STATE REGULATORY REPORTING WAS COMPLETED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

REPORTS OF A SEWAGE-LIKE ODOR WERE MADE WHEN CSXT TRAIN Q530-03 WAS IN BRUCETON, TN.  AFTER INSPECTION, NO PROBLEMS WERE NOTED.  THE TRAIN PROCEEDED TO NASHVILLE, WHERE THE ODOR WAS REPORTED AGAIN.  THE TRAIN WAS YARDED IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RADNOR YARD, AT WHICH TIME THE CONDUCTOR REPORTED THE ODOR FROM UTLX 57882.  INVESTIGATION OF DOCUMENTATION REVEALED THE CAR CONTAINED PULP MILL LIQUID.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CONTRACTOR REPORTED TO THE YARD FOR REPAIRS TO THE CAR.  THE INITIAL CONTRACTOR FOUND THE VAPOR LINE PIPE BROKEN OFF BELOW THE PLUG.  ANOTHER CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO RETHREAD THE VAPOR LINE PIPE.  THE PIPE COULD NOT BE RETHREADED, AND A TEMPORARY SLEEVE WAS INSTALLED TO SECURE THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.  UPON OFF-LOADING THE CAR MUST BE SHOPPED FOR PERMANENT REPAIR.

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TRAINMASTER ADVISED THAT TANK CAR, GATX21655, LOAD ANILINE, TO HAVE A STICKY SUBSTANCE ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK AND AN ODOR WAS DETECTED NEXT TO THE CAR.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE CAR.  HE FOUND NO SIGN OF A LIQUID LEAK.  HE CONFIRMED THERE IS A STICKY RESIDUE ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND A SLIGHT ODOR.  THE TRAINMASTER NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE, NOVEON CORP, BUT THEY COULD NOT RESPOND.  THE SHIPPER, CROMPTON, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CROMPTON AUTHORIZED CSXT TO DISPATCH AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR AND MAKE REPAIRS.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED NO VISIBLE SIGN OF A LIQUID LEAK BUT 2 OF THE 8 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  ONE OF THEM WAS ONLY HAND TIGHT.  THE RESIDUE ON TOP OF THE CAR INDICATED THAT THERE HAD BEEN A LEAK FROM THE AREA OF THE LOOSE MANWAY BOLTS.  THE CONTRACTOR TIGHTENED THE TWO BOLTS AND ENSURED THAT ALL THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE WRENCH TIGHT.  HE CLEANED THE RESIDUE OFF THE TOP AND SIDE OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO BE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NARRI SCORE:  100    5*(5+5+0)*(2+0)   CAUSE CODE:  200

A MECHANICAL DEPT SUPERVISOR INSPECTED THE CAR AND REPORTED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE "B" END BOTTOM SLIDE GATE AND THERE WAS A PILE OF PRODUCT UNDER THE CAR UP TO THE SLIDE GATE.  THE SHIPPER, SOLUTIA INC, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK AND RECOVER THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT A LOCKING LEVER HAD JUMPED OUT OF ITS NOTCH AN ALLOWED THE SLIDE GATE TO VIBRATE OPEN ABOUT 1/4 INCH.  THEY CLOSED THE SLIDE GATE AND THE PRODUCT LEAK STOPPED.  TWO DRUMS OF PRODUCT WERE RECOVERED FROM THE TRACK UNDER THE CAR.  THIS MATERIAL IS TO BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  THE CONTRACTOR CHECKED THE OTHER 3 BOTTOM SLIDE GATES AND REPORTED THEY WERE ALL CLOSED & PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION. column168: DRIVER INATTENTION DURING LOADING PROCESS. RE-EMPHASIZE PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES TO INSURE COMPLIANCE.  DISCIPLINARY ACTION AS APPROPRIATE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE TWO HUNDRED FIFTY GALLON TOTE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS RELEASED AND WERE CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE VALVE ON THE TOTE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING FLOOR DRY, GLOVES, TYVEK SUITS, BOOTIES AND SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM AND WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED ON THE TOTE BIN AND THE TOTE WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ON MAY 18, 2003 FIRE BROKE OUT BETWEEN 4 VEHICLES INVOLVED IN A MULTI-VEHICLE COLLISION IN OVILL, TEXAS.  THE FIRE MELTED ALL 80 DRUMS OF HERBICIDE RELEASED 250 GALLONS OF DIESEL AND CONTAMINATED 60 YARDS OF SOIL. PROTECT ENVIRONMENTAL OF HALTOM CITY, TEXAS PLACED GRANULAR ABSORBENT ON THE FREE STANDING DIESEL AND SWEPT THE MATERIAL UP.  PERSONNEL THEN PUMPED OUT ALL 80 DRUMS OF HERBICIDE THAT WAS MIXED WITH WATER FROM THE RED OAK FIRE DEPARTMENT AND TRIPLE RINSED THEM.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND THEN BACKFILLED.  BERMUDA SOD WAS PLACED ON THE EFFECTED AREAS AND IS BEING WATERED EVERY 4 DAYS UNTIL THE SOD TAKES.  ALL MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF AT VARIOUS LOCATIONS IN THE DALLAS FORT WORTH AREAS.

AT 18:26 ON 5/15/03 IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PACKAGE IN BELLY "31" IN TAIL N413UP WAS LEAKING.  UPS PROCEDURES ARE FOR THE EMPLOYEE TO "DON'T TOUCH, LEAVE AREA, NOTIFY SUPERVISOR" ONCE THE SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED, A RESPONDER WAS BROUGHT IN TO TEST THE CHEMICAL TO DETERMINE IF IT WAS HAZARDOUS. AFTER NUMEROUS TESTS, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID WAS A SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION THAT IS HIGHLY CORROSIVE.  THE PACKAGE WAS UNDECLARED.  PROPER PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED TO NEUTRALIZE AND SOLIDIFY THE CHEMICAL.  CUSTOMER SERVICE WILL FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER.

column168: ON MAY 2, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 1140 HOURS, RAILWAY TANK CARS UTLX 92465, UTLX 901106, UTLX 98261, UTLX 901913, AND GATX 26569, ALL LOADS, VINYL CHLORIDE, STABILIZED/2.1//UN1086//RQ WERE DERAILED ADJACENT TO 10033 IMC ROAD, UNIMAN CORPORATION.  FOUR CARS WERE TURNED OVER ON THEIR SIDES, AND ONE CAR, UTLX 98261, WAS DERAILED UPRIGHT.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, THE LOCAL SHERIFF EVACUATED THE UNIMAN INDUSTRY PLANT ADJACENT TO THE INCIDENT (14 PEOPLE) AND EVACUATED 6 HOMES (10 PEOPLE) FOR A TOTAL OF 24 PEOPLE EVACUATED.  THE EVACUATION WAS IMPLEMENTED AT 1325 AND LIFTED AT OR BEFORE 1500 HOURS.  THE LOCAL SHERIFF DID NOT HAVE A SCIENTIFIC, SOUND CAUSE FOR EVACUATING THE AREA, BUT DID SO BASED ON HIS LIMITED TRAINING AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BACKGROUND. DRIVER ARRIVED AT PLANT FACILITY AND WAS INSTRUCTED WHERE TO OFF-LOAD THE PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER HOOKED UP TO THE CUSTOMERS CONNECTION AND STARTED THE OFF LOADING PROCESS AND WAS ABOUT 25 MINUTES INTO THE OFF LOADING PROCESS WHEN THE OFF LOADING HOSE RUPTURED.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE OFF LOADING PROCESS DOWN.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND THE PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE PRODUCT AND PUT IT INTO THEIR RE PROCESSING SYSTEM.  THE HOSE WAS CURRENT IN ITS INSPECTION DATES.  IT WAS FOUND THAT THE DRIVER HAD CRIMPED THE OFF LOADING HOSE AND THAT COULD HAVE WEAKENED THE HOSE AND CAUSED THE RUPTURE.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER UNLOADING AND INSPECTION PROCEDURE WHILE OFF LOADING.

column168: THE CTL DRIVER ARRIVED AT US BATTERY IN AUGUSTA, GA TO MAKE A DELIVERY. THE DRIVER MADE CONTACT WITH PLANT PERSONNEL AND INSTRUCTION WERE GIVEN TO THE DRIVER AND THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE OFF LOADING AREA AND SAMPLES OF THE PRODUCT WERE TAKEN.  THE DRIVER FOR CTL MADE HIS CONNECTIONS TO THE RECEIVERS OFF LOADING LINE IN ORDER TO TAKE A SAMPLE. AFTER THE SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AND CHECKED THE APPROVAL WAS GIVEN FOR THE PRODUCT TO BE OFF LOADED.  THE DRIVER FOR CTL STARTED TO PRESSURIZE THE CARGO TANK WITH PLANT AIR PRESSURE.  BEFORE THE DRIVER OPENED THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE TANKER THE DOME LID GASKET SEAL WAS BROKEN AND PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE DOME LID AREA.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY PLANT PERSONNEL BY PUTTING DOWN BAGS OF SODA ASH THAT WOULD ALSO NEUTRALIZED THE PRODUCT.  AFTER SPEAKING TO A PLANT REPRESENTATIVE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ASSISTANCE WOULD BE NEEDED TO PROPERLY CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  C & B FOSTER WAS CONTACED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP AND TO DISPOSE OF THE PRODUCT PROPERLY.  THE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND DRUMMED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. ENVIRONMENTAL ALTERNATIVES WERE CONTACTED TO PICK UP THE DRUMMED MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL OF THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL.  THE PRODUCT WAS PICK UP AND A PROFILE WAS RAN TO DETERMINE THE TYPE OF DISPOSAL THAT WOULD BE REQUIRED. THE DRUMMED MATERIAL WAS TAKEN TO SOUTHEASTERN CHEMICAL FOR DISPOSAL AT 755 INDUSTRIAL BLVD. IN SUMTER, GA 29151.  (ATTACHED IS A COPY OF THE NON HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST.)  THERE WERE NO INJURIES RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT. CORRECTIVE ACTION:  AFTER A DISCUSSION WITH PLANT PERSONNEL AS TO THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL A DETERMINATION WAS MADE AND CORRECTIONS WERE MADE IN ORDER FOR THE CUSTOMER TO RECEIVE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER WAS REMOVED FROM DISPATCH PENDING AN EVALUATION.  THE FOLLOWING DAY A CONFERENCE CALL WAS CONDUCTED WITH THE DRIVER'S TERMINAL MANAGER, DRIVER AND SAFETY MANAGER TO DISCUSS IN  DETAIL THE EVENTS THAT TOOK PLACE.  THE DRIVER WAS FOUND NOT PROPERLY FOLLOWING OFF LOADING PROCEDURES AS PER CTL COMPANY POLICY.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED AND RETRAINED BY CTL'S SAFETY MANAGER AND TERMINAL MANAGER AS TO THE PROPER OFF LOADING PROCEDURES AND THE SAFE HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

SPILLED PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME & IMPACTED SOIL WAS LATER REMEDIATED BY ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES ESTABLISHED A 5-MILE PERIMETER FOR EVACUATION & ROAD CLOSURES. APPROX. 95 PEOPLE AFFECTED BY THE EVACUATION UNTIL 2116 HRS. CDT (5/08), AFTER WHICH THE PERIMETER WAS REDUCED TO ONE MILE & APPROX. 15 PEOPLE REMAINED IN EVACUATED STATUS. KANSAS STATE HIGHWAY 177 WAS CLOSED UNTIL APPROX. 1700 HRS. CDT, 5/09/03. (B) BNSF TRAIN IN PROCESS OF SLOWING AFTER RECEIVING TORNADO WARNINGS WITH STRAIGHT LINE WINDS FORECASTED UP TO 70 MPH & ENCOUNTERING HIGH WIND VELOCITY, DERAILED 38 RAILCARS ON MAIN TRACK DUE TO THESE HIGHT STRAIGHT LINE WINDS. SHPX 240270 DERAILED IN A PILE RELEASING AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF RESIDUE PRODUCT HEEL AFTER OTHER DERAILING RAIL EQUIPMENT CRUMBLED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING/ MANWAY BONNET. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, ONE EXPOSED LIQUID VALVE & ONE EXPOSED VAPOR VALVE FOUND SHEARED OFF, LEAVING NO INTERNAL PRESSURE IN THIS TANK CAR. AN ESTIMATE OF ONE-HALF OF RESIDUE PRODUCT HEEL ESCAPED FROM THESE VACATED ORIFICES. THE REMAINDER OF RESIDUE PRODUCT WAS PURGED FROM THIS TANK CAR AT THE SCENE OF THE DERAILMENT.

THE TRAIN MASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S DUVAL YARD IN JACKSONVILLE, FL REPORTED THAT 40-FOOT CONTAINER, SUDU 446373 ON FLATCAR FEC70470, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT OUT THE REAR DOORS. CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PERSONNEL RESPONDED ALONG WITH AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR. THE FREIGHT FORWARDER, COLUMBUS LINES, INC, WAS NOTIFIED. THEY ADVISED THAT ROHM HAAS WAS THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER. ROHM HAAS WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR USED ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO CONTAIN THE LEAKAGE. THE CONTAINER WAS UNLOADED OFF THE FLATCAR AND THE DOORS WERE OPENED. THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH 72 PLASTIC 55-GALLON DRUMS. FIVE (5) DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED BY WOOD USED TO BRACE THE LOAD. APPROXIMATELY 165 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE 5 DRUMS WAS SPILLED. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER, CRXU430180. ON 05-28-03, A CSXT CONTRACTOR PREPARED TO BLOCK AND BRACE THE CRXU430180 FOR SHIPMENT WHEN THEY DETECTED A STRONG PRODUCT ODOR INSIDE THE CONTAINER. ALL THE DRUMS WERE OFF LOADED AND INSPECTED. SEVEN (7) DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED TO HAVE BULGED TOPS OR BROKEN METAL BANDS AROUND THE DRUMHEADS. THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE FROM THESE DRUMS. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE RELOADED ON THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED AND RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO COLUMBUS LINES. A TOTAL OF 9 1/2 DRUMS OF LIQUID PRODUCT (7 DAMAGED DRUMS AND 2 1/2 DRUMS OF RECOVERED PRODUCT) WERE PROCESSED FOR DISPOSAL ACCORDING TO ROHM HAAS INSTRUCTIONS. THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP ACCORDING TO GUIDANCE FROM THE FL DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION.

column168: DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO RAIL SIDING AND CALLED AHEAD TO DETERMINE STATUS OF RAIL CARS. THE DRIVER THERE SAID THE RAIL CAR HE WAS UNLOADING FROM WAS ALMOST EMPTY, BUT HE'D PREP THE NEXT CAR FOR THE INCOMING DRIVER. UPON ARRIVING, THE INCOMING DRIVER WAS INFORMED THAT THE RAIL CAR WAS LEAKING. THE DRIVER INVESTIGATED, AND FOUND A SMALL LEAK FROM A CAP ON TOP OF THE RAIL CAR, BEHIND THE VAPOR VALVE. HE REMOVED THE CAP AND OBSERVED A WHEEL VALVE AND THUMB SCREW WITH MINUTE AMOUNT OF LIQUID WEEPING FROM IT. HE ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN BOTH THE THUMB SCREW AND THE VALVE, BUT NEITHER STOPPED THE LEAK. DRIVER ACTIVATED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES AND CONTACTED THE CORPORATE OFFICE TO REPORT THE LEAK. DRIVER WAS ADVISED TO UNLOAD THE RAILCAR. RAIL CAR WAS EMPTIED OF LIQUID, DEGASSED AND THEN SENT FOR REPAIR. THERE WERE NO COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR, AND NO EVACUATIONS WERE MADE. APPROXIMATELY 20 POUNDS OF AMMONIA WERE RELEASED.

ON TUESDAY 5/13/03 WE DELIVERED A LOAD OF L.S DIESEL TO ROADWAY EXPRESS IN BIRMINGHAM AL. 7500 GALLONS WAS ORDERED. PRODUCT INTEGRITY SHEET WAS SIGNED. AS THE LAST COMPARTMENT EMPTIED THE FUEL BEGAN TO COME OUT THE VENT PIPE. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE P.T.O ON THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH OIL DRY AND SPILL PADS. WE NOTIFIED ROADWAY PERSONNEL OF THE SPILL AND THEY NOTIFIED THE STATE OF ALABAMA WE REQUESTED THAT ROADWAY CHECK THE CAPACITY OF THE ABOVE GROUND TANK BEFORE THE DRIVER UNLOADS.

WE ALSO MADE CONTACT WITH OUR ORIGIN TERMINAL "PAS" FOR THEM TO TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION ON IMPROPER LOADING.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRACTOR TRAILER COMBINATION TRAVELING DOWNHILL THROUGH A SERIES OF CURVES ON A STEEP GRADE. LOADED TRAILER PUSHED TRACTOR INTO A JACKNIFE AS IT CAME OUT OF A SHARP RIGHT TURN AND INTO A SHARP LEFT TURN. DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO RECOVER AND TRACTOR STRUCK HILLSIDE SLIDING BACK ONTO ROADWAY. MOMENTUM AND SHIFTING LIQUID LOAD CAUSED THE COMBINATION UNIT TO ROLL TO THE RIGHT AND ON TO ITS TOO. IT CAME TO REST AGAINST THE HILLSIDE WERE A ROCK OUT CROP PUNCTURED THE REAR MOST COMPARTMENT. THIS CAUSED 2,000 GALLONS OF FUEL TO SPILL INTO A DITCH. THE TRAILER HAD 5 SEPARATED COMPARTMENTS WITH THE LAST WITH A CAPACITY OF 2650 GALLONS. ALL BUT THE LAST REMAINED TIGHT AND LEAK FREE. ALL OTHER PRODUCT WAS SAFELY EVACUATED AND TAKEN TO THE DESTINATION. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE DITCH  WHICH WAS REMOVED AND SENT TO  A REMEDIATION FACILITY WITHIN HOURS OF THE INCIDENT.

WE HAD A DRIVER LOAD SULFURIC ACID FROM A RAIL SITE CARLIN NEVADA FRO DELIVERY TO THE BARRICK GOLD MINE LOCATED 26 MILES NORTH OF CARLIN. AFTER LOADING AND IN ROUTE TO HIS DELIVERY IT WAS DISCOVERED WHAT WAS LATER FOUND TO BE A DEFECTIVE VALVE ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT OF THE TRAILER EVERY TIME HE PULLED A GRADE IN THE ROAD. THIS CAUSED THE LOST OF ABOUT 26 GALLONS OF ACID. THE CLEANUP UP CAUSED THE CLOSING OF AN EXIT AND ENTRANCE RAMP IN CARLIN NEVADA TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. IT LATE CAUSED THE CLOSING OF A COUNTY ROAD THAT LEADS TO THE ENTRANCE OF THE MINE PROPERTY ABOUT 20 MILES AWAY. BOTH LOCATIONS CAUSED THE ROAD TO BE SHUT DOWN FOR ABOUT 2 1/5 HOURS. THIS AREA WAS VERY RURAL AND CAUSED NO DAMAGE TO AND AREAS. THERE WERE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER FORM THE MINE WAS PRESENT AND APPROVED OF THE CLEAN UP.

column168: DRIVER REMOVED DUST CAP FROM UNLOADING LINE SPILLING APPROX. 5-10 GALLONS. DRIVER FAILED TO MAKE SURE THE UNLOADING VALVE WAS CLOSED BEFORE REMOVING THE DUST CAP.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY MISSION.

TWO FACTORS WERE RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS INCIDENT:  1.  THE CONSIGNEE ORDERED MORE PRODUCT THAN THEIR STORAGE TANK'S CAPACITY AT THE TIME THE PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED.   2.  BECAUSE OF THE LOCATION OF CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK, TWO-WAY RADIOS ARE USED BY BOTH THE CARRIER'S EMPLOYEE AND A CUSTOMER REPRESENTATIVE TO MONITOR THE UNLOADING OF PRODUCT INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  THE TWO-WAY RADIO WAS IMPROPERLY USED BY THE CUSTOMER REPRESENTATIVE, ALLOWING THE EXCESS PRODUCT ORDERED TO OVERFLOW THE STORAGE TANK.  THE USE OF TWO-WAY RADIOS IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS WAS REVIEWED WITH THE CUSTOMER AS WELL AS THE CARRIER'S EMPLOYEES IN A EFFORT TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.

ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT AT AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S COOPERATION HAS INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S.  THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

CSXT WITH OLIN'S COOPERATION HAS INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004. EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR

column168: A CHIEF SEAHAWK TANKER TRUCK COLLIDED WITH ANOTHER VEHICLE AND OVERTURNED ALONG THE EASTERN SHOULDER OF HIGHWAY 65 NORTH APPROXIMATELY 0.5 MILES NORTH OF LESLIE, ARKANSAS.  AN ESTIMATED 2,500 GALLONS OF UNLEADED FUEL WAS RELEASED INTO THE DRAINAGE DITCH ALONG HIGHWAY 65.  THE LESLIE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED FIRST AND CONSTRUCTED EARTHEN BERMS TO RETARD MOVEMENT OF FUEL.  VACUUM TRUCKS WERE THEN USED TO EVACUATE FUEL AND IMPACTED STORMWATER FROM THE DITCH.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS THEN EXCAVATED WITH A BACKHOE.  APPROXIMATELY 5,439 GALLONS OF FUEL AND IMPACTED STORMWATER WERE RECOVERED.  APPROXIMATELY 400 CUBIC YARDS OF HYDROCARBON IMPACTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED FROM THE SPILL AREA.

FIRST RESPONDERS ON THE SCENE NEEDED TO MAINTAIN A SAFE DISTANCE, AND WAITED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT AROUND 2:09 AM. AND OUR COMPANY C.A.T. WERE NOTIFIED AT 8:00 AM APPROXIMATELY.

column168: FILE:  3277 D, SHIPPER:  RICHARD ALLAN SCIENTIFIC, AWB#; BTL 8967606028 DEN. ON 05/08/03 AT 1745 (MTN) A DELIVERY DRIVER RETURNED TO THE DENVER DOCK TO UNLOAD HIS FREIGHT AND NOTICED A PACKAGE LEAKING WITH A STRONG ODOR PRESENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE DELIVERY VAN ALONG WITH ONE OTHER PACKAGE THAT HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH THE LEAKING PACKAGE.  THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS IDENTIFIED AS A HAZMAT SHIPMENT WE HAD DELIVERED EARLIER IN THE DAY AND THEN PICKED BACK UP FROM THE CONSIGNEE.  THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WAS PULLED FROM THE BOX, AREA CLEARED AND SHIPMENT CONTAINED.  I CALLED AIRBORNE EXPRESS HAZMAT SUPPORT CENTER AT APPROX 1766 WHO ARRANGED THE HAZMAT RESPONSE.  THE CONTRACTED RESPONSE TEAM (ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION, 6820 N BROADWAY UNIT 1, DENVER, CO, 80221) ARRIVED AND TO MITIGATE THE SPILL APPROXIMATELY 2000 (MTN). ACCORDING TO ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION THIS SHIPMENT WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT CONTAINED 1 X 4 L  PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF "FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (ETHANOL, FORMALDEHYDE), 3, UN 1889, PG II". THE CLOSURE ON THE BOTTLE WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURE CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THE BOTTLE TO LEAK 4 L OF ITS CONTENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT HAD CORRECT MARKINGS, LABELS AND A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

RMCC ADVISED DOUG KENNEY, MYO, REPORTED GATX 23154 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  MR. SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO NEFF YARD, ISOLATED THE CAR, AND PERFORMED AN INSPECTION.  A BUCKET HAD BEEN PLACED UNDER THE VALVE TO CAPTURE AS MUCH OF THE PRODUCT AS POSSIBLE BUT HIGH WINDS WERE BLOWING MUCH OF THE ALCOHOL OVER THE TOP OF THE BUCKET.  MR. SEKAVEC CLIMBED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF TURN.  FURTHER, THE PACKING GLAND FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LOOSE APPROXIMATELY TWO TURNS. MR. SEKAVEC SHUT THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND TO SECURE THE OPERATING ROD.  FINALLY, MR. SEKAVEC OPENED THE AIR VALVE AND RELIEVED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR.  AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR, MR. SEKAVEC FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS NOT COMPLETELY SNUG.  THE CAP WAS REMOVED AND THE GASKET TURNED OVER SO A NEW SURFACE WOULD BE EXPOSED AND THE CAP WAS REINSTALLED AND TIGHTENED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED AS THE PRODUCT EVAPORATED RAPIDLY. NARRI:  5(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80.  CODE:  148

column168: ON 5-8-03 AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS, AN E-CYLINDER, FILLED WITH OXYGEN, COMPRESSED, HAD A MAJOR MALFUNCTION WHEN THE VALVE SEPARATED FROM THE CYLINDER, RELEASING THE CONTENTS AT THE APRIA HEALTHCARE FACILITY LOCATED AT 16 CREEK PARKWAY, BOOTHWYN, PA. APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE, PHILIP RILEY, HAD JUST REMOVED THE CYLINDER FROM A FILL RACK IN THE TRANSFILL DEPARTMENT AND PLACED IT ON A SHIPPING CART. IMMEDIATELY AFTER PLACING THE CYLINDER HORIZONTALLY ON THE CART THE VALVE SEPARATED FROM THE CYLINDER, RELEASING THE 679 LITERS OF OXYGEN, COMPRESSED.  THE VALVE IMPACTED RILEY IN THE LOWER ABDOMEN. RILEY WAS TRANSPORTED TO KROZER-KEYSHAN ER FOR A PUNCTURE WOUND IN HIS RIGHT HIP AND RECEIVED FOLLOW UP TREATMENT AT TAYLOR HOSPITAL'S CENTER FOR OCCUPATIONAL HEALTH.  HE WAS RETURNED TO DUTY ON 5-22-03. EXAMINATION OF THE VALVE (SHERWOOD) AND CYLINDER (LUXFER) REVEALED THAT THE THREADS ON THE VALVE APPEAR TO BE INTACT BUT THE TREADS ON THE CYLINDER APPEAR TO BE STRIPPED.  THE VALVE AND CYLINDER WERE QUARANTINED, PENDING FURTHER INVESTIGATION. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE CYLINDER HAD BEEN RECEIVED IN A SHIPMENT OF 405 E-CYLINDERS FROM PACIFIC CYLINDERS, 4890 HANNOVER, AFFTON, MO 63123. ORDER "17571-001 PO#00310747.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 160 OF THESE CYLINDERS WERE STILL AT THE FACILITY, UNFILLED, AND THEY WERE ALSO PLACED QUARANTINED.  A PICK UP HAS BEEN PLACED ON THE OTHER 244 AND THEY WILL BE SEGREGATED UPON THEIR RETURN FROM PATIENTS. REPRESENTATIVES OF APRIA HEALTHCARE, RISK MANAGEMENT AND PACIFIC CYLINDERS ARE IN THE PROCESS OF IDENTIFYING A THIRD PARTY TESTING FACILITY, WITH NO CONFLICTS OF INTEREST, TO EXAMINE AND TEST THE CYLINDER.

column168: ON MAY 25, 2003, AT APPROXIMATELY 2030, CAR NUMBER FMLX 17020 WAS REPORTED BY CREW FLO93-25 TO HAVE SOME PRODUCT DRIPPING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR CAUSING A BURNING TYPE SMOKE ON THE GROUND BETWEEN THE RAIL.  I WAS CALLED BY THE OPERATION CENTER AT 2055 AND ARRIVED ON SCENE IN THE APPLETON, WI YARD AT 2150.  BY THE TIME I ARRIVED I DID NOT SEE ANY SMOKE COMING FROM THE THREE AREAS RANGING FROM THE SIZE OF A SOFTBALL TO THE SIZE OF A BASEBALL WHERE PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND.  DURING MY INVESTIGATION I FOUND THE SHIPPER FAILED TO APPLY THE VENT ASSEMBLY AFTER LOADING THE CAR, THIS HAD CAUSED PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT, UNKNOWN HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING ENTIRE TRIP, I CAN ONLY COMMENT ON WHAT WAS ON THE GROUND IN APPLETON.  AFTER ASSESSING THE SITUATION I CONTACTED CHEMTREC, PER CN POLICY, AT 2130, THE CHEMTREC INCIDENT REPORT NUMBER IS 05252003015, I STATED TO THEM THE SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL AND NO OTHER RESOURCES WERE NEEDED.  THERE WAS ONLY 2 OF THE 4 BOLTS AND THE GASKET NEEDED TO APPLY THE ASSEMBLY STILL ON TOP THE CAR, I APPLIED THE GASKET AND PLACED THE 2 BOLTS DIAGONAL FROM EACH OTHER AND TIGHTED THEM DOWN.  THE CONSIGNEE IS IN THE SAME YARD AS THE CAR IS NOW,  ONLY ABOUT 300 YARDS AWAY, THE CAR WILL BE SAFE TO TRAVEL TO GET UNLOADED,  ANYWHERE ELSE THE OTHER 2 BOLTS WILL HAVE TO BE APPLIED BEFORE IT WILL BE OK TO MOVE.  IN TALKING TO THE SHIPPER THEY STATED THAT THIS ASSEMBLY WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN REMOVED FOR ANY REASON DURING THE LOADING OF THIS CAR.  INCIDENT SEVERITY INDEX 5(5+5+0)X(2+0) = 100 CAUSE CODE = 426

column168: DRIVER (ROGER W DEGON) WAS NORTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 395 NEAR CHEWELAH, WASHINGTON.  THE TRUCK TRACTOR AND SEMI-TRAILER DRIFTED RIGHT OFF THE ROADWAY;  THE DRIVER OVERCORRECTED AND ROLLED BOTH VEHICLES ONTO THEIR RIGHT SIDE.  A 250-GALLON PORTABLE TANK WAS DAMAGED AND SPILLED ABOUT 7 GALLONS OF WEEDAR 64 HERBICIDE.  THIS MATERIAL IS A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE (100 POUND RQ);  HOWEVER, THE SPILL DID NOT MEET THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY. HIGHWAY 395, A MAJOR TRANSPORTATION ROUTE WAS CLOSED.  ON MAY 13, 2003, AT ABOUT 12:35 PM, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT #644839). THE WASHINGTON STATE PATROL, WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY AND THE WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION WERE ON SCENE AND SUPERVISED THE CLEANUP.  THE SPILLED HERBICIDE AND CLEANUP RESIDUE WILL BE DEPOSED OF AT AN APPROVED HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THE TRUCK TRACTOR AND SEMI-TRAILER WERE TOWED AWAY.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL, TREATED AND RELEASED.  THE DRIVER DID NOT RECEIVE A CITATION AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.   HOWEVER, THE WASHINGTON STATE PATROL DID REQUIRE THE DRIVER TO SUBMIT TO A CONTROLLED SUBSTANCE TEST.  AS OF JUNE 3, 2003 WE HAVE NOT RECEIVED A TEST RESULT OR AN ACCIDENT REPORT WHICH WAS REQUESTED. DRIVER DISPOSITION/ INCIDENT PREVENTION IF THE CONTROLLED SUBSTANCE TEST IS POSITIVE, THE DRIVER WILL BE TERMINATED.  OTHERWISE, THE DRIVER WILL BE MEDICALLY EVALUATED FOR DRIVING FITNESS AND WILL ATTEND A DEFENSIVE DRIVING TRAINING PROGRAM.

column168: V-1 (TRANSPORT VEHICLE DRIVEN BY ROBERT D KAUFFMAN) WAS HEADED SOUTHWEST ON K-42 ( A 2 LANE HIGHWAY) IN SUMNER COUNTY KANSAS. V-2 (PICKUP TRUCK DRIVEN BY LARRY DEAN AUE) WAS ALSO HEADED SOUTHWEST ON K-42. V-2 APPROACHED V-1 FROM THE REAR AT A HIGH SPEED AND ATTEMPTED TO PASS V-1 ON IT'S LEFT SIDE. V-2 HIT THE LEFT SIDE OF V-1'S CARGO (A CLASS 7, LSA, REACTOR VESSEL HEAD) CAUSING A TEAR IN THE SCO WRAP BUT NO DAMAGE TO THE CARGO.  THERE WAS NO SPILL OR CONTAMINATION.  V-2 PROCEEDED TO COLLIDE WITH 2 ONCOMING CARS. V-2'S VEHICLE WAS DISABLED AND THE DRIVER ABANDONED HIS VEHICLE AND LEFT THE SCENE.  V-2'S DRIVER WAS LATER APPREHENDED AND ARRESTED FOR DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE OF ALCOHOL.  THE SUMNER COUNTY SHERIFF'S OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND DEPUTY SHERIFF SCOTT GOFORTH (#35) RESPONDED TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE STATE OF KANSAS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT OFFICE( LETICIA ARZATE PH 785-575-7376).

column168: ON 5-20-03 PASSENGERS BRAD GRANDCLAIR, 6213 APACHE DR, THE COLONY, TX. CHECKED IN A TOOLBOX FOR HIS TRIP TO PHL. THE FLIGHT WAS DFW-MDW-PHL; THE INBOUND TO PHL WAS TZ238 TAIL N313TZ. THE INBOUND FLIGHT PASSENGER WAS BEING OFF LOADED AND THE DELTA GROUND CREW STARTED DOWN LOADING THE PASSENGER BAGS FROM BIN 3. AT 23:10 THE DELTA CREW NOTICE A TOOLBOX IN THE AIR CRAFT WAS ON FIRE SO THEY PUSHED IT OUT OF THE A/C TO THE GROUND. THE GROUND CREW THEN MOVED THE BURNING TOOLBOX AWAY FROM THE A/C. THE CREW NOTIFIED THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPT BUT BEFORE THEY ARRIVED THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED BY CORY COPELAND OF DELTA GROUND CREW. THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE WAS DETERMINED TO BE A SMALL HAND HELD PROPANE TORCH STORED IN THE TOOLBOX. THE OWNER WAS QUESTION ABOUT THE TORCH AND STATE THAT HE NEVER HAD PROBLEMS BEFORE TRAVELING WITH THE TOOLBOX. AND TORCH. HE ALSO STATED THAT HE DID NOT KNOW THE TORCH HAD FUEL IN IT. THE TORCH WAS HELD IN PHL STATION SO THAT IT COULD BE TURN OVER TO TSA OR FAA. THE A/C HAD NO DAMAGED AND NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED.

PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS CECILIA HOCKEY AND ELWOOD BOHL DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN 10 X 20 OZ METAL AEROSOL SPRAY CANS OF "DO-IT ALL GERMICIDAL FOAMING CLEANER". THIS BOX HAD PREPRINTED ORM-D MARKINGS THAT HAD BEEN COVERED UP BY ORIENTATION ARROWS.  THE CLOSURE ON THESE CANS WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURE ON TWO OF THESE CANS CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THEM TO LEAK THEIR ENTIRE CONTENTS OF 20 OZ EACH.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE SUBSTANCE.  SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 1214  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column168: A PROPANE TRANSPORT INTERNATIONAL (PTI) FILLING TRUCK WAS ON SITE TO FILL THE DIESEL AST.  A LONG HOSE AND SHORT HOSE MADE UP THE FILLING HOSE, AND THE PTI DRIVER, PAUL DURNEZ, DISCONNECTED THE LONGER HOSE, USING ONLY THE SHORT HOSE BETWEEN THE TANK AND TRUCK.  THE CONNECTION ON THE TANK END WAS REINFORCED WITH RUBBER BUNGIE CHORDS.  AFTER CONNECTIONS WERE MADE AND FILLING COMMENCED, THE TRUCK WAS LEFT UNATTENDED.  AS STATED BY MR. DURNEZ, "PUMP VIBRATIONS CAUSED THE EARS TO MIGRATE TO (THE) OPEN POSITION AND (THE) OFF-LOAD HOSE BUILT ENOUGH PRESSURE TO COME LOOSE."  INITIALLY THE DRIVER INDICATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WERE RELEASED, AND AN UNKNOWN CALLER MADE A 911 CALL.  HAZMAT RECEIVED A CALL NOTIFYING THEM OF A SPILL AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM.  THE FUEL FOLLOWED THE GRADE OF THE LOT EAST APPROXIMATELY 46 FEET TO  A STORM WATER WASH THAT RUNS ALONG THE WEST SIDE OF SANFORD STREET.  THE FUEL FOLLOWED THIS "GUTTER" SOUTH TOWARDS HIGHWAY 6 & 50 APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET.  RAINY CONDITIONS AIDED IN WASHING ALL OF THE FUEL ALONG THE PATH OF LEAST RESISTANCE, LEAVING BEHIND LITTLE RESIDUE.  CONTAMINATION THEN PROCESSED TO FOLLOW GRAVITY TO A STORM WATER DITCH RUNNING ALONG HIGHWAY  6 & 50, FLOWING WEST.  BECAUSE OF RAINY CONDITIONS, WATER WAS PRESENT IN THE DITCH AND ACTED AS A BARRIER BETWEEN THE FUEL AND SOIL (DIESEL FUEL LAID ON TOP OF THE WATER).  UPON ARRIVAL, HAZMAT WAS ON SITE AND HAD CONTAINED THE DIESEL RELEASE WITHIN THE STORM WATER DITCH BETWEEN HIGHWAY 6 & 50 AND THE ACORN STATION BY CONSTRUCTING A SAND DIKE.  THE SAND DIKE WAS LOCATED ADJACENT TO AN I-70 SIGN IN FRONT OF THE WEST GATE INN.  A MAKESHIFT OIL/WATER SEPARATOR WAS CONSTRUCTED WITHIN THE DIKE USING A LENGTH OF 4" PVC THAT WAS LAID AT A 45-DEGREE ANGLE TO THE SURFACE OF THE WATER.  THE LOW END WAS SUBMERGED IN THE CONTAMINATED SIDE OF THE DIKE, AND THE HIGH END EMPTIED INTO THE UNAFFECTED SIDE OF THE SAND DIKE.  ALONG THE ENTIRE LENGTH OF THE DITCH FROM THE STAND DIKE TO SANFORD STREET, FREE PRODUCT COULD BE SEEN ON THE WATER SURFACE.  A VERY STRONG ODOR WAS PRESENT. RAINBOW MOUNTAIN SERVICES (BOB) ARRIVED ON SITE BY REQUEST OF D. SOPOCI AT APPROXIMATELY 1:15 PM.  THE DEWATERING PROCESS BEGAN ON THE IMMEDIATE WEST SIDE OF THE ENTRANCE WHERE A CULVERT IS LOCATED.  APPROXIMATELY 6,000 GALLONS WERE REMOVED FROM THIS LOCATION, CAUSING WATER ON EITHER SIDE TO FLOW TO THIS POINT.  A SECOND SAND DIKE WAS LAID AT THIS TIME ABOUT 15 FEET FROM THE EAST SIDE OF THE ENTRANCE TO ISOLATE EACH SIDE OF THE DITCH, WITH THE ENTRANCE ACTING AS THE HALF WAY POINT.  DEWATERING CONTINUED ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE DITCH, AND MOVED TO THE EAST SIDE ONCE MOST OF THE WATER WAS REMOVED FROM THE WEST.  ONCE DEWATERED, WATER AND PRODUCT WAS ALLOWED TO SEEP FROM THE DUTCH WALLS, POOL AND WAS REMOVED.  THE DEAWTERING PROCESS RESUMED UNTIL 8:00 PM, WHEN ALL OF THE RECOVERABLE WATER AND FUEL WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH.  APPROXIMATELY 18,000 GALLONS OF DITCH WATER AND DIESEL FUEL WAS REMOVE

column168: ON MAY 31, 2003, AT APPROXIMATELY 22:55 HOURS, I WAS CALLED BY RADIO TO RESPOND TO LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE ON THE BLACK BELT.  I RETRIEVED THE SPILL CART AND ALL REQUIRED GEAR INCLUDING SCBA AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL I WAS INFORMED THAT A PARTIAL EVACUATION OF THE BELT WAS ORDERED.  I NOTICED A VERY STRONG IRRITATING VAPOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE ON THE BELT AND IT HAD AN OBVIOUS LEAK.  I IMMEDIATELY DONNED THE SCBA AND REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE BELT AND PLACED IN THE SPILL TRAY.  I WAS INFORMED BY TRISH MORRIS, THE BLACK BELT SUPERVISOR THAT TWO INDIVIDUALS HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO VAPORS AND WERE EXPERIENCING SOME DIFFICULTIES.  I CLEANED THE AREA ON THE BELT THAT HAD THE MATERIAL ON IT AND THEN PROCEEDED TO THE PSC AREA TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP PROCESS.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE, I OBSERVED FOUR 1 LITER BOTTLES OF URETHANE ACCELERATOR LIQUID INSIDE.  I ALSO OBSERVED THE CAP HAD BEEN BROKEN LOOSE AND ONE BOTTLE OF THE MATERIAL HAD SPILLED, CONTAMINATING THE OTHER THREE BOTTLES.  I USED THE DECISION TREE AND FOLLOWED THE CLEAN UP PROCEDURE AND NOTIFIED MR. DAVID BROWN IMMEDIATELY.  THE MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A LARGE YELLOW HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTAINER AND SEALED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  I THEN WENT AND INTERVIEWED THE 2 EMPLOYEES EXPOSED TO THE FUMES.  MRS. WEST WAS EXPERIENCING A SLIGHT HEADACHE AND MR. JAMES WASHINGTON EXPERIENCED SOME THROAT IRRITATION.  BOTH STATED THAT THEY WERE FINE AND NEEDED NO FURTHER MEDICAL ATTENTION.  BOTH EMPLOYEES RETURNED TO THE BLACK BELT AND CONTINUED TO WORK.
PACKAGE WAS LOADED AT BOTTOM OF WALL WITH 63 POUND BOX ON TOP.

PRELOADER (CHRIS COX) NOTICED PKG LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OF CONTAINER.  PKG WAS PLACED IN SPILL TRAY WITH ABSORBENT CLAY IN THE BOTTOM.  HAZMAT RESPONDER (BARRY LUCUS) WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

AT 1740HRS ON 5-25-03. CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT WILLIE WILSON, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS REPORTED LOADED TANK NATX 37178 LOCATED IN TRACK 305, ENGLEWOOD YARD WAS LEAKING. MGR LERCH RESPONDED AND ON ARRIVAL, NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE COMBINATION HOUSING AND DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR. INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED IT TO BE SHELL FULL AND UNDER A NITROGEN BLANKET. PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE OF THE COMBINATION HOUSING AND FROM THE LIQUID VALVE FOUR BOLT FLANGE. AFTER DETERMINING THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC, AND SPOKE TO MR TIM KELLY. EMERGENCY COORDINATOR FOR CHEVRON PHILPS CHEMICAL ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL TO REDUCE THE LOAD. EAGLE PERSONNEL REDUCED THE LOAD BY APPROXIMATELY 2500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT, PROVIDING THE CAR WITH 13 INCHES OF OUTAGE. ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE CHECKED WITH NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED. CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. AFTER CAR IS OFF LOADED. IT WILL BE SHOPPED FOR INSPECTION OF THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE AND PRESSURE PLATE. THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, NOR ANY REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT. RELEASED PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR AND ATMOSPHERE.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT 1353 HRS ON 5-28-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THE FOLLOWING.  TROY SLINKARD, DIRECTOR TERMINAL OPERATIONS REPORTED WHILE CONDUCTING HUMING OPERATIONS, TANK CAR CELX 20714 HAD STRUCK DERAILED TANK CAR PPRX 33824 LOCATED IN THE 1-64 FROG, ENGLEWOOD YARD BOWL TRACKS; HOUSTON, TX.  UPON IMPACT, CAR CELX 20714 SUSTAINED A HEAD PUNCTURE FROM THE DRAW BAR OF CAR PPRX 33824.  ON IMPACT, THERE WAS A RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THIS RELEASE WAS FOLLOWED BY AN IMMEDIATE LOCAL EVACUATION UNTIL SAFE PARAMETERS COULD BE ESTABLISHED.  UPON BEING NOTIFIED, MGR LERCH REQUESTED SHIPPER CONTACT VIA CHEMTREC, AND SPOKE TO MR. ROB ST JOHN, EMERGENCY COORDINATOR FOR CELANESE AND REQUESTED PRODUCT SPECIFIC INFORMATION AND AN MSDS.  ADDITIONAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE THEN MADE REQUESTING ASSISTANCE FROM THE CENTER OF TOXICOLOGY & ENVIRONMENTAL HEATH FOR AIR MONITORING AND HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY MGR LERCH AND REGIONAL CTS MGR O'BRIEN REVEALED A SMALL HEAD PUNCTURE ON THE "A" END, RIGHT SIDE BOTTOM CORNER OF THE SEAM WELD WHERE THE HEAD AND SHELL OF THE CAR JOIN. WITH THE USE OF WOODEN WEDGES AND A CONTAINMENT POOL, THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT WAS KEPT MINIMAL.  WHEN CTEH ARRIVED, AIR MONITORING EFFORTS BEGAN AND SAFETY ZONES WERE FURTHER DEFINED.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE BY HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL TO OFF LOAD THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR INTO TRUCKS. AFTER COMPLETION OF PRODUCT TRANSFER, THE AFFECTED AREA AND SPILLED MATERIAL WERE NEUTRALIZED AND A DEODORANT WAS THEN APPLIED.  ON 5-29-03, SAMPLES OF PRODUCT WERE TAKEN FROM THE TRUCKS TO CHECK FOR PURITY, WHICH WAS LATER DETERMINED TO BE INTACT.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE TO TRANSPORT THE PRODUCT FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, NOR ANY REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: GARY WALKER, CONDUCTOR, REPORTED A LEAKING TANKCAR IN THE CITY OF INDUSTRY AT ORANGE AVENUE AND VALLEY ON THE ALHAMBRA SUBDIVISION, MP 498.80. THE TANKCAR WAS UTLX 130466 LOCATED ON YARD TWENTY-FOUR, TRACK TWENTY-SIX ON THE EAST END OF THE YARD, THE SECOND CAR OUT. THE TANKCAR WAS CURRENTLY ENTRAINED ON THE MWCW 21 IN THE INDUSTRY YARD. ERNIE SIROTEK JR., REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WERE NOTIFIED. THE LEAK WAS THE RESULT OF A MISALIGNED GASKET ON THE FILL NOZZLE. IT LEAKED LESS THAN ONE PINT THAT WAS CONTAINED TO THE RAILCAR. THE GASKET WAS REALIGNED AND PROPERLY SECURED. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE STATE, CHEM TREC AND THE SHIPPER, JONES HAMILTON. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

TIM POST, RAMP MANAGER, REPORTED BLACK, TARRY SUBSTANCE WAS OBSERVED AROUND THE DOORS OF CONTAINER CCLU 241523 LOCATED AT DOOR 4, CUSTOMS DOCK, IN THE ICTF YARD. MR. POST FURTHER STATED NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED AND THE SUBSTANCE DID NOT REACH THE GROUND. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND IT TO BE AN 80 DRUM LOAD, DOUBLE STACKED, WITH APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT RELEASED AND SOLIDIFIED ON THE FLOOR. MANAGER COOPER SPOKE WITH PROCESS CHEMICALS, PRODUCT MANUFACTURER, LOCATED IN WINTERHAVEN FLORIDA, WHO WAS MAKING ARRANGEMENTS WITH TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL TO REWORK THE LOAD. INITIAL EVALUATION SHOWED THE DOUBLE STACKED DRUMS WERE SECURED IN PLACE WITH TY GARD. BOTH THE TOP AND BOTTOM TIER CORNER DRUMS HAD THE SIDES CAVED INWARD AND CRUSHED. THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE IS NORMALLY SEEN WHEN THE LOAD IS LOOSE AND HAS SHIFTED TO THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER. INFORMATION DEVELOPED FROM THE MANUFACTURER THIS PRODUCT IS DRUMMED HOT AND ALLOWED TO COOL BEFORE SHIPPING. BASED UPON THE CONDITION OF AT LEAST HALF OF THE DRUMS, THE PRODUCT WAS NOT COOL BEFORE THE DRUMS WERE SEALED, CAUSING THEM TO IMPLODE. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, ONE DRUM WAS LOCATED AT THE LEFT REAR DOOR, FLOOR LEVEL, THAT HAD THE BOTTOM CHIME WORN THROUGH FROM RUBBING AGAINST THE LEFT SIDE WALL 'D' RING. AS THE PRODUCT WAS STILL LIQUID AT THE TIME, APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS RAN ONTO THE FLOOR, COOLED, AND SOLIDIFIED. THE RESIDUE WAS CLEANED FROM THE FLOORING AND THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. A TOTAL OF 36 DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE IN SUCH CONDITION THAT THEY WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT, AND WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT. A PORTION OF THE LADING WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO CCLU 267288. BOTH CONTAINERS WERE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.
